recmndText:
It is my pleasure to write in support of Mr. Po Ting Lin’s application to the BioPro A+ program. I have known Bo Ting since July of 2017 when he got the admission into the MS program in Graduate Institute of Biomedical Electronics and Bioinformatics at National Taiwan University, where I am an Associate Professor. I am his MS thesis advisor and we have had weekly meetings for most parts of the past two years. In this letter I am comparing his performance to all the MS students I have supervised in the past 13 years.
During my supervision of Po Ting on his MS studies over the past two years, I am most impressed by his versatility to learn many skills in different disciplines. Although his background training in undergraduate study was medical laboratory science, he was determined to transform himself into an engineer from the first day of joining my group. The first project he took on in my group is developing new technique to non-invasively identify the type of white blood cells. In this project he built a confocal optical detection system to measure backscattering spectra from individual white blood cells and applied digital signal processing techniques to analyze the measured spectra. The second year he learned the principle and optical setup of quantitative phase microscopy (QPM). Then he came up with a proposal to apply QPM to detect apoptosis of living cells due to the exposure to a high degree of oxidative stress. Not only did he bravely take on new projects, but he also has done a pretty good job. This demonstrates that he is both highly intelligent and perseverant to achieve his goals. In addition to participating in research projects, he also took many courses to strengthen his programming skills, analytical ability and engineering training. 
Besides academic activities and performance, I also have close observations on Po Ting’s personality. He is very humble, friendly to peers, always wanting to help, and yet persistent to achieve his goals. In summary, I give my full support to Po Ting’s application to the BioPro A+ program. Given his ability, motivations and skills/knowledge he has acquired over the past two years, I think that more exposure to innovative research topics and the stimulating environment in your institute is an excellent opportunity for him to widen his vision and grow tremendously. And I think he will make the most of this opportunity to both improve himself as a researcher and advance the technology. If there is any question regarding my recommendation, please feel free to contact me.

Sincerely Yours,
Kung-Bin Sung

It is my pleasure to write in support of Mr. Tzu-Chia Kao’s application to the BioPro A+ program. I have known Tzu-Chia since the Fall semester in 2016 when he took “Introduction to Biomedical Engineering” course in his junior year in EE department at National Taiwan University (NTU). He later took “Special Research Project” under my supervision in his senior year. After graduating from college he got the admission into the MS program in Graduate Institute of Biomedical Electronics and Bioinformatics at NTU, where I am an Associate Professor. I have been his MS thesis advisor for one year. Therefore, I have adequate opportunities to evaluate his research abilities and overall academic potential. In this letter I am comparing him to all the MS students I have supervised in the past 13 years.
    First of all, in my opinion Tzu-Chia ranks in the top 10% in research abilities among all of the MS students I have supervised. He got his BS degree from the EE department which is the most competitive undergraduate program in science and engineering in Taiwan. His GPA in undergraduate studies was well above average, and he has gained solid trainings in electrical engineering, programming and engineering mathematics. What makes him stand out is his attitude toward learning and researching. In the three courses that I taught him, I noticed that he was always very focused on what I was saying while thinking hard and critically to understand the materials. He often asked questions that either were interesting due to novel points he came up with, or reminded me to express my points more clearly. I would say that he’s the best student a teacher would want in his/her class due to his responsiveness and critical thinking. In research, I witnessed his growth from an undergraduate student participating in our existing projects to a mature graduate student who can independently search the literature to find suitable methods, implement the best method he has found and test/evaluate the performance. Through the discussions I have had with him, I found that he always thinks critically and tries to understand new concept and knowledge thoroughly. His excellent programming skills have helped him implement modeling algorithms he learned from the literature to efficiently and effectively solve problems at hands. His abilities to do advanced modeling are evidenced by a journal paper he and another student co-authored, and by several conference papers. 
    In addition to very high academic performance and potential, I also have direct observations of Tzu-Chia’s personality. Despite being a first-year MS student, Tzu-Chia is very proactive to take the initiative and improve the quality of lives for all the students in my lab. Not surprisingly, he is very friendly and will to help to fellow students. Therefore, I think Tzu-Chia is a very good team worker and has shown traits of a good leader. In summary, I give my full support to Tzu-Chia’s application to the BioPro A+ program. Given his ability and motivations, I think that more exposure to innovative research topics and stimulating environment in the host institution is an excellent opportunity for him to widen his vision. And I think he will make the most of this opportunity to both improve himself as a researcher and advance the technology. If there is any question regarding my recommendation, please feel free to contact me.
